<subSubSection pageId="125" pageNumber="126" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="125.[151,1437,814,2030]" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1282,1309]" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">Description:</emphasis>
test very fragile (oral side missing) with a subrounded (greatest weight = TL). Anterior end truncated in lateral view; frontal ambulacrum sunken. Larger tubercles mostly absent, except for the edge of the anterior ambulacrum. Apical disc posterior with four genital pores. Internal fasciole shield-shaped, longer than wide (width = 42% length), almost half of the test length; 35–36 pores on each side of ambulacrum III within the fasciole, arranged in the following manner: small pores aligned proximally in a single series relatively; in the mid-section larger pores somewhat transversely elongated and more crowded forming an irregular biserial arrangement (area of largest weigh of the fasciole); at the anterior end circular pores more widely spaced, forming again a single series. Specialized penicillate tube feet present. Rows of the pair petals somewhat convergent and depressed; petal IV and V with 9(IVa)–14(IVb) and 12(Vb)–11(Va) pore pairs, respectively. Periproct round and truncated. Anal fasciole expanding along the sides of the periproct onto the aboral side. Spines relatively uniform through the aboral region with the exception of elongated spines of the frontal ambulacrum forming an apical tuft. No pedicellaria were found, except for a few small tridentate (=200 μm) with leafshaped valves with irregularly serrate edge. Colour: naked test cream, spines light brown and brown tube feet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="126" lastPageNumber="127" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="125.[151,1437,814,2030]" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1751,1777]" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">Remarks:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Marques" box="[327,510,1751,1778]" firstAuthor="Marques" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref189697" refString="Marques, V. M. (1983) Peuplements benthiques de Acores, 1 - echinoderms. Arquivo do Museu Bocage, AII (I), 1 - 7." type="book chapter" year="1983">Marques (1983)</bibRefCitation>
was the first to report 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pennant" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[782,1070,1751,1777]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis box="[782,1070,1751,1777]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">Echinocardium cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the archipelago. We have not found the specimen(s) in the Vasco Marques collection at the Bocage Museum. Nevertheless, later 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirtz &amp; Debelius" firstAuthor="Wirtz" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" refId="ref204573" refString="Wirtz, P. &amp; Debelius, H. (2003) Mediterranean and Atlantic invertebrate guide. ConchBooks, Hackenheim, 305 pp." type="book" year="2003">Wirtz &amp; Debelius (2003)</bibRefCitation>
published a photograph portraying an 
<emphasis box="[776,993,1823,1849]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pennant" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[776,914,1823,1849]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cordatum">E. cordatum</taxonomicName>
in situ
</emphasis>
in Faial Island. Unfortunately, none of the authors have specified at which depth this species seems to occur in the archipelago (see below remarks under 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mortensen" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[151,297,1895,1922]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="flavescens">
<emphasis box="[151,168,1896,1921]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[182,297,1895,1921]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">flavescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="125.[151,1437,814,2030]" lastBlockId="126.[151,1437,153,323]" lastPageId="126" lastPageNumber="127" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">
The specimen housed in 
<collectionCode box="[480,625,1931,1957]" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">DBUA-ECH</collectionCode>
collection was rather damaged, lacking the entire oral area. Regardless, this specimen presents the typical double arrangement of the pores of ambulacrum III of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pennant" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[1157,1295,1967,1994]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis box="[1157,1174,1968,1993]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1189,1295,1967,1993]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In contrast, the specimen lacks many features expected in a typical 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pennant" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[782,920,2003,2030]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis box="[782,799,2004,2029]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[814,920,2003,2029]" italics="true" pageId="125" pageNumber="126">cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, having a weakly sunken ambulacrum III ab- orally. On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pennant" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[438,574,153,179]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis box="[438,455,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[468,574,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised by a high degree of morphological variation and the observed departure from the norm is well inside the documented variability of this species (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Higgins" box="[1115,1270,189,215]" firstAuthor="Higgins" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" pagination="451 - 475" refId="ref184378" refString="Higgins, R. C. (1974) Specific status of Echinocardium cordatum, E. australe and E. zealandicum (Echinoidea: Spatangoida) around New Zealand, with comments on the relation of morphological variation to environment. Journal of Zoology, 173, 451 - 475. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1974. tb 04127. x" type="journal article" year="1974">Higgins 1974</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Higgins" box="[1281,1341,188,215]" firstAuthor="Higgins" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" pagination="507 - 515" refId="ref184449" refString="Higgins, R. C. (1975) Observations on the morphology of Echinocardium cordatum (Echinoidea: Spatangoida) from diverse geographical areas. Journal of Zoology, 177, 507 - 515. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1975. tb 02255. x" type="journal article" year="1975">1975</bibRefCitation>
). Unfortunately, only one 
<typeStatus box="[357,405,225,251]" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">type</typeStatus>
of pedicellariae was found. The small tridentate pedicellariae are similar to what 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" pagination="1 - 200" refId="ref192287" refString="Mortensen, T. (1907) Echinoidea (Part 2). In: The Danish Ingolf-Expedition 1895 - 1896. 4 (2). Bianco Luno, Copenhagen, pp. 1 - 200." type="book chapter" year="1907">Mortensen (1907)</bibRefCitation>
described for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pennant" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[390,528,261,287]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis box="[390,407,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[422,528,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, this 
<typeStatus box="[709,757,261,287]" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">type</typeStatus>
of pedicellariae is not diagnostic, and similar morphologies can be found in other species known from the NE Atlantic such 
<taxonomicName authority="(Mortensen 1907)" authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1907" baseAuthorityName="Mortensen" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[868,1226,297,323]" class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Echinocardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="flavescens">
<emphasis box="[868,1014,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">E. flavescens</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[1029,1217,297,323]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" pagination="1 - 200" refId="ref192287" refString="Mortensen, T. (1907) Echinoidea (Part 2). In: The Danish Ingolf-Expedition 1895 - 1896. 4 (2). Bianco Luno, Copenhagen, pp. 1 - 200." type="book chapter" year="1907">Mortensen 1907</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
